replies.bodyText:
The first parameter is for the DSL text, while the second one is for the DSL text enhanced by the recognized marker information. Such a call invocation could look like for example:
	@Test def test001() {
		'''
			package foo
			class Foo {
				def m() {
					val a = new Object
					val b = new Object

					if (a == null) {}
					if (b != null) {}
				}
			}
		'''.testMultiQuickfix('''
			package foo
			class Foo {
				def m() {
					val a = new Object
					val b = new Object

					if (a <0<==>0> null) {}
					if (b <1<!=>1> null) {}
				}
			}
			-------------------------------
			0: message=The operator '==' should be replaced by '===' when null is one of the arguments.
			1: message=The operator '!=' should be replaced by '!==' when null is one of the arguments.
		''', '''
			package foo
			class Foo {
				def m() {
					val a = new Object
					val b = new Object

					if (a === null) {}
					if (b !== null) {}
				}
			}
			--------------------------
			(no markers found)
		''')
	}

What are everyone's thoughts on an API that works more like...?
val initialText = '''
    package foo
    class Foo {
        def m(Object a, Object b, Object c) {
            if(a == null || b != null || c === null) 0 else 1
        }
    }
'''
val expectedText = '''
    package foo
    class Foo {
        def m(Object a, Object b, Object c) {
            if(a === null || b !== null || c === null) 0 else 1
        }
    }
'''
val markerText = '''
    0: message=The operator '==' should be replaced by '===' when null is one of the arguments.
    1: message=The operator '!=' should be replaced by '!==' when null is one of the arguments.
'''


testMultiQuickfix(initialText, expectedText, markerText)

Perhaps making the markerText value optional.
